{"id":14880915,"mediaExerciseId":"d66ad92d-7c91-4a32-b9f2-220f783ccb57","exerciseName":"17","chapterName":"5","chapterTitle":"Introduction to Valuation:The Time Value of Money","groupId":612293,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":148,"solutions":[{"id":6073256,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we take the same premise that we are poised to buy a new Ferrari. However, here we are presented with a better rate of return to our investment (a mutual fund) than in exercise 9. We want to calculate how much we need to invest today to reach our goal in 9 years when we turn 30.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"We know the following values:\n\n|||\n|--|--|\nFerrari's price| $245,000 \nInvestment time (years)|9\nMutual fund rate of return | 11.20%","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"To calculate how much we need to invest today we are going to use the Present Value (PV) formula. \n\n\n$$ PV = \\frac{FV}{(1+r)^ t}$$\n\n*Where:*\n- FV is the future value\n- r is the applied rate\n- t are the periods of time\n\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Know we just need to use the values we know to obtain the present value of our investment. \n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\nPV &= \\frac{\\$245,000 }{(1+0.112)^9}\\\\\n\\\\\n&= \\boxed{\\$94,237.34}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nOur investment today should be **$94,237.34** if we want to afford the Ferrari in 9 years.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"PV = $94,237.34","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":true,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"9eceb86c-21c1-4edb-8b7b-eb52ad875f35","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880916,"exerciseName":"18","page":148,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"4a703296-7efd-4454-abd8-a9265ae6a5b7","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-5-questions-and-problems-18-4a703296-7efd-4454-abd8-a9265ae6a5b7"},{"id":14880917,"exerciseName":"19","page":148,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"ac7b5ff9-2bbd-4218-8e8e-e19ecd8802f9","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-5-questions-and-problems-19-ac7b5ff9-2bbd-4218-8e8e-e19ecd8802f9"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880914,"exerciseName":"16","page":148,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"039bb787-af6b-4237-aa07-ca870eb5f194","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-5-questions-and-problems-16-039bb787-af6b-4237-aa07-ca870eb5f194"},{"id":14880913,"exerciseName":"15","page":148,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"c4c61179-51ec-436c-9d46-6e84d33e0e85","